 sixteen eminent scientists. Their views on the meaning and relevance of their work are interwoven with inspiring autobiographical accounts of how formative life experiences led to their research, conclusions, and activities. These narratives, based on personal interviews, are by such world-renowned figures as James Lovelock, originator of the Gaia hypothesis; Paul Ehrlich, author of The Population Bomb and founder of Zero Population Growth; Max Nicholson, a founder of the World Wildlife Fund; and Sherwood Rowland, who discovered the chemistry of atmospheric ozone depletion. These essays read like an intimate conversation with the world's top scientists. This collection also provides a view of the international development of ecology as a scientific enterprise. Life Stories demonstrates the important role of the scientific community in fostering worldwide awareness of the dangers facing the Earth today, and in seeking solutions for tomorrow. Young readers will find this book inspiring for the life stories it tells. Readers of all ages will find here a profound, urgent, and compelling message about the future of life on Earth.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aEnvironmental Conservation & Protection. 4aNature. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Lester, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrlich, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFiror, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoldgate, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKendall, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovejoy, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLovelock, James, econtribu